This question tests the ability to design per-tenant runtime feature controls using a Redis-backed flag store with TTL-based caching. It evaluates understanding of multi-tenancy, caching strategies, fallback logic, and operational observability in a CNF gateway context.

## Key Concepts

- Per-tenant feature flags in a Kubernetes sidecar architecture
- Redis key design using tenantID:path format
- TTL-based caching with 60-second expiration
- Fallback mechanism to global default flags
- Runtime observability via /flags/status endpoint

## Code Example

```javascript
// Feature flag evaluation in CNF sidecar
class FeatureFlagService {
  constructor(redisClient) {
    this.redis = redisClient;
    this.globalDefault = true;
  }

  async evaluateFlag(tenantId, path) {
    const key = `${tenantId}:${path}`;
    const cached = await this.redis.get(key);

    if (cached !== null) {
      return cached === 'true';
    }

    return this.globalDefault;
  }

  async getStatus(tenantId) {
    const flags = await this.redis.keys(`${tenantId}:*`);
    const activeFlags = await Promise.all(
      flags.map(async (key) => ({
        path: key.split(':')[1],
        enabled: (await this.redis.get(key)) === 'true',
        ttl: await this.redis.ttl(key)
      }))
    );

    return {
      tenantId,
      flags: activeFlags,
      timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
    };
  }
}
```

